lg.l: First issu'd from Perfumer's Shops
A Crowd of fashionable Fopps,
They ask'd her, how she lik'd ye Play?
Then told the Tattle of the day.
A duel fought last night at two,
About a Lady──you know who:
Talk'd of a New Italian come,
Either from Muscovy or Rome.
Gave Hints of who & who's together;
Then fell to talking of ye Weather.
Last night was so extreamly fine,
The Ladies walk'd till after Nine.
Then in Soft voice, & speech absurd,
With Nonsence every second word,
With fustian from exploded Plays
They celebrate her Beauty's Praise;
Run o'r their Cant of stupid Lies,
& tell ye murthers of her Eyes.
A party next of glitt'ring Dames
From round ye Purlieus of Sṭ James
Came early out of pure Good Will
To see the Girl in Deshabille.
Their Clamour lighting from yeir chairs
Grew louder all ye Way up stairs:
At Entrance loudest.──Where they found
The Room with Volumes litter'd round.
Vanessa held Montaigne, & read,
Whilst Mrs Susan comb'd her head.
They call'd for Tea, & chocolate
And fell into their usuall Chat,
Discoursing with important Face
On Ribbands, Fanns, & Gloves, & Lace.
Shew'd Patterns just from India brought
And gravely ask'd her, wt she thought?
Whether ye Red or Green were best?
And wt they cost? Vanessa guesst,
As came into her Fancy first;
Nam'd half ye Rates, & lik'd ye Worst.
To Scandall next────
────What aukward Thing,
Was that last Sunday, in the Ring?
I'm sorry Mopsa breaks so fast,
I said, her Face wou'd never last.
Corrinna, with that youthfull Air,
Is Thirty & a Bitt to spare.
Her fondness for a certain Earl
Began, when I was but a Girl;
Phillis, who but a month agoe
Was marry'd to ye Tunbridge Beau,
I saw coquetting t'·other night,
In publick, wth that odious Knight.
They rally'd next, Vanessa's Dress:
That Gown was made for good Qu. Bess!
Dear Madam! let me set your head:
Don't you intend to put on Red?
A Petticoat wthout a Hoop!
Sure you are not asham'd to stoop:
With handsom Garters at your knees;
No matter, what a Fellow sees.
Away ye fair Detractours went,
And gave, by turns, their Censures Vent.
She's not so handsom in my Eyes!
For wit, I wonder where it lies!
She's fair & clean, & that's the most;
But why proclaim her for a Toast!
A Baby-Face, no Life, no Ayres,
But wt she learnt at Countrey-Fairs.
Scarce knows wt diff'rence is between
Rich Flanders-Lace, & Colberteen.
I'de undertake, my little Nancy
In Flounces has a better Fancy.
With all her Wit, I wou'd not ask
Her Judgmt, how to buy a Masq overkue;
We begg'd her, but to patch her Face,
She never hit one proper place;
Which ev'ry Girl at five years old,
Can do, as soon as she is told.
I own, that out-of-fashion Stuff
Became the Creature well enough.
The Girl might pass, if we cou'd get her
To know the World a little better.
To know the World! a modern Phrase
For Visits, Ombre, Balls, & Plays.
